stylometry: The tradeoff managers must consider when dealing with waiting lines is the service cost and the waiting cost. If the service cost is higher, this means that there are more servers, which in turn decreases the waiting time. But you must decide if incuring more costs for servers is valuable enough to decrease the waiting time. If the waiting cost is high, this means the customers wait longer, but there is not as high of a service cost. The objective is to find a balance where you can have acceptable waiting time and number of servers. The objective is not just to decrease the waiting time by as much as you can, because this means you could hire as many servers you want until the waiting time is zero. Instead, you want to find the best balance between the two.
